Rocky, Adam, and Aisha manage to free themselves and destroy the Putties and the sleeping device. Meanwhile, the Rangers manage to free the Sword of Light just as Zedd destroys the deserted city. Back at the Command Center, the Rangers inform Zordon that Serpenterra proved a tough opposition and Jason, Trini, and Zack announce that they plan to back out from the Peace Conference as they are needed as Power Rangers. Zordon tells them that their destiny lies outside the team now and as they succeeded in their final quest, the Rangers will be able to continue with new Rangers in their place and he presents them with the new Red, Black, and Yellow Rangers: Rocky, Adam, and Aisha. Using the Sword of Light, Tommy transfers the powers from Jason, Trini, and Zack and the new Rangers appear morphed. Zordon thanks Jason, Trini, and Zack for their loyal service and wishes them well in their futures before the three of them leave. Zedd meanwhile returns to Earth with Serpenterra to attack. The new team go into action and summon the Thunderzords. At first Serpenterra proves a worthy opponent, but it proves to have a flaw. It loses energy very quickly and Zedd is forced to retreat. Back at the Command Center, the Rangers see Jason, Trini, and Zack off via the viewing globe and celebrate their first victory with Rocky, Adam, and Aisha.

Back at the Command Center, the Rangers inform Zordon that Serpenterra proved a tough opposition and Jason, Trini, and Zack announce that they plan to back out from the Peace Conference as they are needed as Power Rangers. Zordon tells them that their destiny lies outside the team now and as they succeeded in their final quest, the Rangers will be able to continue with new Rangers in their place and he presents them with the new Red, Black, and Yellow Rangers: Rocky, Adam, and Aisha. Using the Sword of Light, Tommy transfers the powers from Jason, Trini, and Zack and the new Rangers appear morphed. "On the ground of his eminence as a chemist"
"On the ground of his important researches in the domain of organic chemistry"
"On the ground of his studies in the camphor group and among the organic derivatives of nitrogen and silicon"
"On the ground of his distinguished work in chemistry, especially that on optical activity, and on fermentation"
"On the ground of his work in physical chemistry and more especially on the composition & constitution of alloys"
"For his researches in synthetic organic chemistry"
"For his researches on the complete drying of gases and liquids"
"For his researches on the structure of natural colouring matters"
"For his work on the constitution of the sugars"
"For his work on the theory of ionisation"
"For his work in physical chemistry, especially on the subject of electrolytic solutions"
"For his contributions to physical chemistry and particularly for his theory of membrane equilibrium"
"For his contributions to classical thermodynamics and the theory of valency"
"For his work on the constitution and synthesis of natural products; also for his contributions to the theory of organic reactions"
"For his researches in organic chemistry, particularly those connected with tautomerism and the mechanism of organic reactions"
"For his distinguished researches in organic chemistry"
"For his researches in organic chemistry, and for his work on the synthesis and properties of the cyanine dyes, and more especially for his investigation of novel types of asymmetric molecules"
"For his researches on the molecular structure of carbohydrates"
"For his distinguished work in biochemistry and especially for his fundamental discoveries in the chemistry of alcoholic fermentation"
"For his pioneer work on contact catalysis and his researches on the mechanism of combustion of hydrocarbons and on the nature of flames and on gaseous explosions"
"In recognition of his work on the chemistry of the porphyrins, particularly his determination of their detailed structure by degradation and his syntheses of porphyrins of biological importance"
"In recognition of his distinguished researches on alkaloids and other natural products"
"For having opened up the study of colloidal electrolytes, provided the elements of the guiding theory, and developed the subject"
"For his isolation of deuterium, the heavy hydrogen isotope, and for his work on this and other isotopes in following the detailed course of chemical reactions"
"For his work as a pioneer in biochemical research and especially because of his fundamental contributions to the study of intermediate metabolism"
"In recognition of his distinguished work on the mechanism of chemical reactions"
"In recognition of his many notable contributions to organic chemistry, especially to the chemistry of natural products of physiological importance"
"In recognition of his researches on explosives, analytical methods, the internal structure of diamond, and infra-red absorption spectra"
"In recognition of his extensive researches in the field of organic chemistry and of his recent work in the alkaloid field"
"In recognition of his distinguished work in applying physical methods to problems in organic chemistry"
"In recognition of his outstanding work in the determination of the structure of sugars, starches, plant gums and especially of vitamin C"
"For his structural synthetic studies and achievements in organic and bio-chemistry, with special reference to vitamins B1 and E and the naturally occurring nucleosides"
"For his distinguished researches on the constitution of natural products, especially the plant hydro-carbons and their derivatives"
"For his distinguished contributions to the subject of surface chemistry"
"In recognition of his researches into the chemistry of natural products, particularly the wide range of glycosides, bitter principles and colouring matters containing heterocyclic oxygen atoms"
"For his distinguished work on the applications of quantum mechanics to the theory of valency and to the analysis of the intimate structure of decimal compounds"
"For his distinguished fundamental investigations in organic chemistry"
"In recognition of his distinguished work in physical chemistry and in polymer reactions"
"In recognition of his distinguished contributions to the chemistry of natural products particularly those containing heterocyclic systems"
"In recognition of her distinguished studies in the structure and growth of crystals"
"In recognition of his distinguished work in chemical kinetics, especially in photochemistry"
"In recognition of his distinguished researches in organic chemistry and particularly for his contributions to the structure and synthesis of natural products"
"In recognition of his distinguished pioneering work on the analysis of crystal structure, especially of organic compounds"

"In recognition of his distinguished researches in organic chemistry, particularly on the structure and stereochemistry of natural products of the terpene and steroid series; and the analysis of the conformation of cyclic structures"
"In recognition of his distinguished researches in inorganic chemistry and the discovery and examination of a wide range of new compounds"
"In recognition of his distinguished work on the elucidation of photochemical reactions, and for his study of fluorescence and phosphorescence in relation to the molecular processes concerned"
"In recognition of his pioneering work in chemistry and biology, particularly his elucidation of the photosynthetic pathway for the incorporation of carbon dioxide by plants"
"In recognition of his distinguished contributions to infra-red spectroscopy and its application to chemical problems"
"In recognition of his distinguished contributions to synthetic organic chemistry and to the elucidation of the structures of natural products"
"In recognition of his distinguished work in the development of stereochemical concepts and on the structure of alkaloids and antibiotics"
"In recognition of their distinguished joint work on the elucidation of the biosynthetic pathway to polyisoprenoids and steroids"
"In recognition of his distinguished work on the mechanisms of chemical reactions"
"In recognition of his distinguished work in theoretical chemistry"
"In recognition of his distinguished contributions to our understanding of chemical reactions"
"In recognition of his distinguished biosynthetic studies of organic natural products and his development of new reagents for reduction processes"
"In recognition of his distinguished contributions to chemistry especially on the structural investigation of imperfect surfaces and non-stoichiometric materials"
"In recognition of his distinguished researches on coenzyme A and studies of the constituents of bacterial cell walls"
"In recognition of his distinguished contributions to physical chemistry including particularly the reactions occurring in flames"
"In recognition of his outstanding contributions to nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy and its application to chemical and biological problems"

"In recognition of his outstanding and internationally recognized contributions to biosynthesis– his meticulous and logical unravelling of the complex pathways by which alkaloids and porphyrins are elaborated in vivo"
"In recognition of his distinguished contributions to modern synthetic organic chemistry, well illustrated by his impressive total synthesis of vitamin B12"
"In recognition of his distinguished contributions to transition metal chemistry and the understanding of catalysis involving ligating molecules such as olefins or dinitrogen"
"In recognition of his distinguished contributions to the chemistry of natural products including vitamin B12 porphyrins, plant germination factors and insect hormones and pheromones"
"In recognition of his distinguished contributions to organic synthesis and in particular his ingenious applications of acetylenic intermediates"
"In recognition of his distinguished studies of the mechanisms of a wide range of chemical reactions based on semi-empirical wave mechanical calculations"
"In recognition of his distinguished creativity in the fields of biosynthesis and bioorganic stereochemistry"
"In recognition of his distinguished contributions to the theoretical basis of thermodynamic aspects of polymer chemistry"
"For his outstanding work on the structure and reactivity of metal cluster compounds, including pioneering work on carbido and hydrido derivatives, and pi-donor organic molecules"

"In recognition of his early seminal proposal of the ways enzymes deal asymmetrically with symmetrical substrates and his later quantitative analysis of macromolecule interactions which elucidated polymer exclusion effects"
"In recognition of his contributions to the chemistry of human DNA— in particular the discovery and exploitation of hypervariable satellites in the human genome"
"In recognition of his wide-ranging contributions to theoretical chemistry, especially his development and application of techniques for the computation of molecular wave-functions and properties"

"In recognition of his many distinguished contributions to organometallic chemistry, including the discovery that species containing carbon-metal of metal-metal multiple bonds are versatile reagents for synthesis of cluster compounds with bonds between different transition elements"
"For pioneering the quantitative study of free radical reactions in solution, in glasses and in living organisms, particularly using electron magnetic resonance"

"In recognition of his contributions to mechanistic chemistry integrated with enzymology, particularly the application of chemical methods to solve fundamental biological problems of recognition and catalysis"
"Distinguished for the determination and characterization of the molecular spectra of transient species"
"Distinguished for his contributions to bio-organic chemistry, in particular to an understanding of the biosynthesis of beta-lactam antibodies"
"For his pioneering studies of solid-state chemistry, and for the major advances he has made in the design of new materials for heterogeneous catalysis"
"In recognition of his contribution to organometallic chemistry with particular application to catalytic reactions"
"In recognition of his contribution to organotransition metal chemistry and the development of homogeneous catalysis and his work on hydroformylation"
"In recognition of his work on supramolecular chemistry, on self-assembling molecules and on chemical devices"

"In recognition for his pioneering work on the analysis of proteins by combining the methods and ideas of physical-organic chemistry with those of protein engineering thus illuminating such processes as enzymatic catalysis, protein folding, protein-protein interactions and those macromolecule interactions in general that are dominated by the chemistry of the noncovalent bond"

"In recognition of his leading work in inorganic chemistry, particularly his major impact on the chemistry of transition metals and his pioneering research on the unique triply metal-metal bonded dimolybdenum and ditungsten dialkylamides, alkoxides and alkyls, and for the use of these compounds in further important syntheses"

"In recognition of his invention of new synthetic methods applied to the synthesis of complex natural products including those from insects, micro-organisms and plants. Among his most outstanding successes have been the synthesis of avermectin B1a, tetronasin, the milbemycins and indanomycin as well as his important development of short, practical syntheses of oligosaccharides"

"For his pioneering contributions to the understanding of biosynthetic pathways, and in particular for his work on vitamin B12. He is a world leader in his area and the impact of his discoveries are likely to have a significant effect on the way natural product chemistry progresses into the future"
"For his many and varied contributions to molecular spectroscopy and its applications, particularly to astronomy"

"For his work on the application of NMR and other structural methods for studying protein folding and misfolding, especially the formation of amyloid fibrils, leading to novel insights on protein structure and folding"
"For his pioneering work in the field of molecular semiconductors which has now become a large and important area of semiconductor science and technology"
"For his many innovative experimental contributions to a broad area of chemical physics, including molecular reaction dynamics, molecular spectroscopy and most recently, biophysical chemistry"
"For his pioneering contributions to several fields, most recently to the field of dynamic combinatorial chemistry at the forefront of supramolecular chemistry"
"For her ground-breaking and novel use of mass spectrometry for the characterisation of large protein complexes."
"For his seminal contributions to the study of ultrafast reactions and the understanding of transition states in chemistry, and to dynamic electron microscopy."
"For his pioneering protein film electrochemistry allowing exquisite thermodynamic and kinetic control of redox enzymes, exemplified by hydrogenases, key in energy technology."
